result.execSummary:
The defendant James Jessie Davis was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Battery - Domestic Abuse Repeater [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse Repeater, Domestic Abuse Assessments], an unclassified felony, Wisconsin Statutes 940.19(1).
  • Disorderly Conduct - Domestic Abuse Repeater [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse Repeater, Domestic Abuse Assessments], an unclassified felony, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant James Jessie Davis in court with attorney Laura Michelle Habush.  Defendant James Jessie Davis in custody.  Nicolas J Heitman appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Case was set for jury trial and has resolved.
  On motion of the State, Court ordered count 1 amended to BATTERY with Repeater enhancer, contrary to Wisconsin Statutes section(s) 940.19(1) and 939.621(1), a felony.
AS to counts 1 and 3 WITH REPEATER enhancers:    Defendant was advised of constitutional rights and maximum penalties, and further advised that if not a United States citizen deportation is possible. Defendant examined as to plea, and entered a plea of guilty.  Court found defendant freely, voluntarily and intelligently waived all constitutional rights. Plea questionnaire waiver of rights and addendum to plea questionnaire received and filed. Parties stipulated to the criminal complaint as factual basis to sustain defendant's plea. Court found defendant guilty as charged in the Information and ordered a Judgment of Conviction be entered into the record.  The Court advised defendant that as a convicted felon not to possess any firearms/body armor.    Court further advised defendant of voting ineligibility.   
Count 2 is ordered dismissed and read in for sentencing.
Sentencing proceeded.  Statements to the court by all parties and additional statement by Felicia M.
AS TO COUNT 1:
  The Court ordered the Defendant to serve 1 year in the House of Correction, with credit for 162 days time served.    The court orders defendant to pay all applicable costs, fees, assessments and surcharges  as a condition of probation as imposed in count 3  and failure to do so will result in entry of civil judgment.
AS TO COUNT 3:
  The Court sentenced the defendant to serve a term of IMPRISONMENT of 17 MONTHS in the Wisconsin State Prisons, with credit for 0 days time served.  CONFINEMENT of 10 MONTHS and EXTENDED SUPERVISION of 7 MONTHS.  The Court STAYED the sentence and placed the defendant on probation to the State Department of Corrections for a period of 2 YEARS.  
CONDITIONS OF PROBATION:
-Attend and successfully complete Batterers Intervention OR Anger Management and continued programming.
-Mental health evaluation and take all prescribed medication(s), and/or treatment deemed appropriate.
-AODA and recommended treatment including random urine screens/Maintain ABSOLUTE SOBRIETY.
-Parenting classes.
-Attend and successfully complete treatment and counseling programs as deemed appropriate by agent.
-NO CONTACT with the victim, UNLESS requested by victim and then only with prior approval of agent or the court.
-3rd party contact for the purpose of time with child(ren) as approved by agent.
-Obtain/maintain employment.
-No contact with firearms.
-NO NEW LAW VIOLATIONS.
-Pay all MANDATORY costs, assessments, surcharges, victim/witness surcharge, domestic violence surcharge, and pay all financial obligations ordered in count 1,and supervision fees as determined by Dept of Corrections.  Any amount remaining due and owing is subject to civil judgment and/or tax intercept or other means. ANY CASH BAIL ON DEPOSIT TO BE APPLIED.
-Provide DNA sample, pay costs and DNA surcharge.
-48 USC Section 922(g)(9) prohibits possession of a firearm and/or ammunition after conviction of a misdemeanor crime of domestic violence.
